,Not Recommended,287980,29026678,Posted: 4 January,all,maybe 10%,"There is a hell and it is circular. ---You will enjoy this game. I enjoyed this game. It is deceptively simple and allows you to cultivate your own preferred playstyle in the absence of any substantive tutorial and with an overly compliant difficulty curve geared towards early success. As someone looking to recline and take in some enjoyment, Mini Metro is sleek and superb - accept the invite and try it, and there's a number of solid hours of glee as individual levels are 'beaten:' with the player ultimately losing, or retiring, with enough points cached to earn an achievement.Mini Metro then politely deadlocks the door and insists that if you want to reach the high scores, to obtain the achievements which are (in this context) the only real signifiers of completion, you'll have to put up with obnoxious RNG and unfavourable spawns. You willrequiresome kind of bizarre foresight to overcome the random placement of the map's stations: four of one kind a row, with the game neglecting to provide you in the weekly update (in-game-time) with the upgrade you require (a tunnel, line, carriage, or whatever it may be given the precise circumstance), and Mini Metro quickly becomes an unpolished turd. The fact that the most exclusive achievements are possessed by a fraction of a percent of the playerbase in the port of a phone game should be evidence enough. Mini Metro is fun, but more of a joyous minimalist idea than a polished, concise video game experience:there is no win state except that which is self-imposed, and if your self-imposition relies even remotely on Steam achievements, then your win state is a monumentous gamble away.I'd have recommended this game for the first 6-8 hours I played it. Now I'm triggered, several attempts at one of the level's achievements later, and I no longer think it is worth the time: other reviewers have praised this game's reward structure, but I think it undeserving. ~"
