,Recommended,287980,21697792,"Posted: 7 March, 2016",all,Trar [99th Calzones],"This is a mostly elegant puzzler that has you constructing stylized light rail lines in big cities and avoiding overcrowding at your stations for as long as possible. There's not much else to it other than daily challenges with leaderboards, a mode that makes all your tracks permanent and a mode that disables terminal overcrowding. It's kind of like ifTrain Valleywas a survival game.There's a couple problems that don't kneecap the game, but are still worth noting. The music is automatically generated from train movement and passenger sounds, which might get grating after a while. Stations pop up seemingly randomly enough, and end-of-week upgrades are determined randomly enough, that games are as much up to chance as they are up to your on-the-spot problem solving ability. At higher levels of play, the game becomes more about micromanagement than triage and strategic planning; ""train warping"" and ""ghost lines"" are terms often used to describe skills that are essential to earning high leaderboard positions and some achievements, but woefully immersion-breaking for a transit game. I still recommend this - I can see it being something you play while you're commuting yourself. Bonus points for having a night mode too."
