76561198344523676,Recommended,287980,29285324,Posted: 15 January,all,schwarzkopfhighpriest,"Good. Insanely good. Not since RCT II have I found as an addictive and mezmorizing game as Mini Metro.At first, you think ""It's a puzzle game!""  No.And then you think ""It's a sim game!"" No.And then you think ""It's a strategy game!"" No.It's all three. And a logistics game too.The beauty of the game lies in its simplicity and its elegance. No fancy graphics to chew up your computer speed. No messy noises to ruin your hearing. No time consuming constructions to build.  It basically takes you back to when strategy/sim games were simple, eloquent & easy to learn how to play... and nearly impossible to master.Taking a few queues from SimCity, Locomotion, Railroad Tycoon & RollerCoaster Tycoon II, Mini Metro is incredibly easy to learn. A few quick rounds in London to get started, and you're off. Each level varies in complexity, challenging issues & equipment. Melbourne for example features same-speed trams that cross your map slowly. Whereas Osaka has high-speed rail links to work with. And Cairo's short car subways fill up quickly.Part of what makes this game so great is the straightforward graphics. No frills. No gimmicks. No flashy BS to showcase a programmer's tiny little....ego. It's brilliant as it has less - and it works by being so much more.Highly addictive. Highly recommended. And possibly in my top 5 games played of all time. (And I go back to the 1980s, kids...)"
