,Recommended,287980,21559963,"Posted: 29 February, 2016",all,jadekiwi,"""Wait, Auckland doesn't have a...""""Oh. OH. I SEE THE JOKE HERE.""Brought the game on the strength of that joke alone. However, the game is strong enough on its own merits that I'm very pleased with my purchase. On endless, you've got a fantastic idle game you can fiddle with while listening to a podcast, trying to up your efficiency. On normal, you've got an intriguing puzzle that requires your constant attention, analysis and problem-solving skills [along with the occasional gamble] as you try and make sure that the people flow so as to not get left standing on a station to the point where their complaints get you shut down.As a side note, I like to imagine that this represents the complete anarchy of people who're waiting on a station platform for too long. An hour is fine, but when they're waiting for a whole day to get to work, they're probably going to start burning things to get your attention.The way you draw 'lines' in both the sense of a metro and in the sense of them being literal lines is a kinaesthetic pleasure. The visual and auditory senses combine to create a meditative yet active and engaging mood. Fantastic work on that sound, by the way. Very few games combine what's happening in the game with the sound the player hears that well. You can see from screenshots, too, the aesthetic appeal of the game. If you don't get some amount of pleasure just from looking at the game, then you might want to check whether or not you actually want to buy it.In normal [which in some ways feels like 'survival', at the end of each week you get an upgrade to your system. These vary from map to map [In Cairo your trains only hold four passengers, in another of the maps you can get fast bullet trains] but you always get another train of some description which you can plop on an existing line or use as the basis of a new one. After accepting this, you get the choice between one of two additional upgrades, both of which you'll sorely need. Perhaps you need another two bridges to complete some loops, or another car to double the capacity of a train, maybe a fourth line so that you can make each more efficient. Whichever you choose, you may within moments regret your bad, stupid choice, because there's now a station on that one little island you've been looking at, wondering how soon you'll need more bridges to access. Now you have to redo a track or two to free up a bridge to make a line that reaches it. And a line it shall be, because although loops are generally more efficient, you just can't do it with that track if you want it to cover where you need it to cover.Thus is the loop of the game. Meet demand. Watch demand rise. Panic. Meet demand.If I must provide some outright negatives, I'll say that the game does what I might call a shoddy job at teaching you the basic controls. The tooltips telling you how to play only pop up once, so if you missed them, good luck. You can fiddle around a bit and make peace with losing a couple of games prematurely in order to work it all out, but some things it doesn't even seem to tell you [at least in enough detail you you'd understand it at first], like the fact you can click in the middle of a line between two stations and drag it to another station to add it to the link. A basic tool at your disposal, though not indespensible, the alternative way to perform the action is more time consuming, which gets in the way of the main appeal of this game, which is its creative flow.That being said, all in all, this is a fantastic minimalist piece of logical art. The couple of issues I had learning the game at first were all resolved within the first hour, and I've had a great time since  then. It's fresh, and even after you understand it, the occasional curveball always keeps it interesting, as does the pursuit of perfection.Nice to see a brilliant indie game from NZ."
,Recommended,287980,23648077,"Posted: 19 June, 2016",all,FilthyLeech,It all comes down to the commuter wait times. No time wasted on deciding whether to build tunnels or bridges. No pesky budgets to balance. No politics and no legislative restrictions. Just the art of designing the best possible subway system there is. This game is absolutely hands down worth your time and money! I can higly recommend it. ^_^
76561198178101393,Recommended,287980,28920886,Posted: 1 January,all,Evi Song,"This game is somehow both stressful and relaxing.  The music is calm and quiet, and the game itself is very simplistic.  My only major critic is that the tutorial is terribly inadequate-- I had to take to the internet to figure out some stuff that should've been explained originally."
,Recommended,287980,11822257,"Posted: 22 August, 2014",all,Perdix,"TL;DR - Mini Metro is a top-down iconographic map-planning and resource-management simulation in which you build a metro system that somehow manages to pop new stations up at an alarming rate.  Your only resource is time, and you will eventually lose - the satisfaction in this game comes from creating a well oiled machine.  I'd recommend it to anyone who enjoyed building transport networks on Simcity 4 or find themselves building all possible city improvements in Civ just because they like to see the city doing well.This (as of writing) is a game in Beta, but still thoroughly enjoyable.  Your task is to create a metro network by facilitaing the transport of shaped passengers (circle, square, triangle, star etc) with the same shaped stations.  This is done by connecting thestation shapeswith a coloured transport line - a train will automatically carry passengers back and forth along the line's length.The difficulty comes from the fact that each station can only so many passengers - and once a station has been full for 30 seconds, it's game over.  This becomes more and more likely as the map progressively bigger, more stations are added, and more shapes are included - your only tools against this are earned at the end of each week; more trains, more lines, and more carriages.  To throw one more spanner into the works, each map contains a river which can only be travered through the use of 'tunnels' - again, only to be earned at the end of each week.  This causes  for some very difficult decisions to be made about whether you should pick more trains to add to your system, or whether you're going to need to get over the river with one of your lines before the week is out.The aesthetic mirror's the current London Underground colouring and angling - meaning that even when you end up losing the game, looking back over your map is a fairly satisfying experience.I definitely recommend to anyone who enjoys intense resource management and optimising pathing; the skill in this game is in weighing up many different routes simultaneously and evaluating which is the best.  An oddly satisfying experience all the way through; one that will be even better once the music and sound effects have been added into the game."
76561198081730122,Recommended,287980,16455536,"Posted: 16 June, 2015",all,Prycon,Let's Go To The Metro ... Today!
76561198038285890,Recommended,287980,24370883,"Posted: 17 July, 2016",all,buffomounie,"Such a simple concept, and yet so much fun!  The graphics are absolute basic, almost comical, but that does not take away from the gameplay.  The interface is very intuitive, and I found myself playing immediately without even bothering to look up anything about how to play.  This game is relaxing, yet challenging.  You'll soon be trapped by the ""next time I'll do it so much better"" feeling, and before you know it you've been playing for an hour...Your goal is to connect the metro stations together.  New stations pop up at random on the map, and you decide whether to extend an existing train line to service that new station or to create a new line.  You can add extra trains, extra cars, and even extra-fast trains to your lines as the game progresses.  Use your tunnels and bridges sparingly, because you only have so many to work with.  Also, the total number of train lines, engines, and carriage cars are also limited, but you can choose which items you want more of at the end of each simulated week in the game.  When people have to wait too long at a station to catch a train, the game is over.  Simple, right?  Ha!  If only...After you've played a few rounds you begin to think like a traffic engineer.  How can I best eliminate this bottle-neck?  Should I add another line to short-cut between these two large hubs?  Or maybe just add another train to the line?  What about making a loop?  You find yourself trying all sorts of different ideas, and cursing yourself when a new station pops up across the river and you don't have any bridges or tunnels left because you foolishly squandered them early on to make an inner-city loop!Mini Metro has a calm, relaxed atmosphere, and it reminds me a bit of the original Railroad Tycoon, but in this game there is no real economy.  There's nothing to buy, and the supply of track is unlimited.  Your only real adversary is time.  You need to keep the people moving, and the trains only go so fast...  An average game lasts about 10 minutes.Tons of fun, especialy for such a simple concept.  If you liked Sim City or Railroad Tycoon, chances are good that you'll love this game.  And at only 10 bucks, it's pretty cheap too."
