,Recommended,287980,32945845,Posted: 28 June,all,Pelandes,"Minimetro is a small indie game about building and managing an oversimplified underground transport system. The idea itself is very simple, but it is executed masterfully.You get a map with stations (represented by geometrical shapes such as circles or triangles depending of their type) and a set of resources to conect them with underground trains and get the passangers wherever they want to go. Small shapes appear next to the stations representing people waiting for a train (a circle-shaped passanger means that they'll get off on a  circle-shaped station), once a locomotive stops at a station all compatible passangers get out automatically and available passangers fill in the blanks without needing player interaction. What the player has to do is draw lanes for the trains to get to every station and find the most efficient way to do so.Here's the catch, though: passangers will continue to spawn in stations even if they are already filled to the brim, and if more than six passangers are waiting at a non-upgraded station at the same time, then it's ""Overcrowded"" and a timer starts ticking down for you to clear up that mess or otherwise the system colapses and you get a Game Over. For every week that you manage to survive, a new locomotive is given to you to put into the system, and an upgrade of your choosing (extra carriages for train cappacity, extra lines, more tunnels to go under rivers, station upgrades...). As time goes on, the map get progressively and worringly bigger, stations keep popping up randomly and the system gets more and more complex for you to run, eventually breaking down as you fail to keep up. You never win, you just keep going until you just can't manage it anymore.The thing is, even though it sounds like a game that would get dull really fast, it really isn't, and I find miself coming back to it when I'm bored to plug in some music and find out how far I can go this time. Each game is randomly generated and different maps have special quirks for you to mess around with. And there are different game modes for those who want to take it easy or for those who want a real challange.+ The flow of the game is surprisingly well done. You are in control of a perfectly-oiled machine until suddenly you are not anymore and you find yourself struggling to keep four particularly nasty interchanges from overcrowding.+ Each game lasts 10-20 minutes. Perfect for a fun little time waster.+ The achievements themselves present extra challanges for those who have run out of things to do or who are tired of wandering aimlessly and want to be given an specific objective.+ I just can get over how such simple graphics work perfectly for this kind of game. Looks like you are constantly staring an actual Metro map from a real city.- Get the Night Mode going as soon as you can and LEAVE IT ON. Otherwise you'll burn your eyes from constantly looking at a bright pure white background.- You can't save a game on progress. Even if the games are pretty short, you can't leave mid-way through one and come back to it later, which can be very frustrating if you are very close to getting an achievement but you suddenly have to leave to do something else.- Kind of goes with everything I've said so far, but this is a game to play for 10-30 minutes and then leaving it for another day. Extended game sessions WILL get dull.This game gets a 7 out of 10. If you want to play the Alpha prototype, you can head to the developer's site here:https://dinopoloclub.com/minimetro/. Mind that the game has improved quite a bit since then."
,Recommended,287980,32927226,Posted: 28 June,all,Shifty,Really nothing to say here. Enough content for the price and alot of fun once tyou get going. I defintley recommend buying this game.
,Recommended,287980,33039018,Posted: 30 June,all,Ash,"Mini Metro is the perfect game to play to pass the time, or when you don't have much time at all.Although it can be frustrating to watch a station slowly but surely overcrowd, it's all fun and each play won't take you long.You'll start off great, then multiple stations of the same shape will keep spawning, it goes from casual ""connect the dots"" to ""strategic resource management"", all without feeling too high pressure, and maintaining a calm, laid back atmosphere.As someone who loves simulation games, this is quite a stripped down, more puzzle-like approach to a ""metro manager"" style game, and I adore it. It's simple, it looks neat, sounds great and I can't stop going back to it when I need to kill a few minutes.Overall this game is a great way to improve your resource management skills, or just kill some time."
