,Recommended,287980,17879712,"Posted: 4 September, 2015",all,Ogg,"As of today, sept. 4th, 2015, Mini Metro is still in development. But it's already a fully playable (and enjoyable) game.Mini Metro is a minimalist game, in the sense that:- the goal is simple (keep your metro network working as fluidly as possible)- the gameplay elements are simple (as time goes on, you gain more lines, train, tunnel...)- the ergonomics are simple (draw a line between two stations and you've built a new metro line ; click and drop a train on a line and it'll immediately work on its own schedule)- the look is simple (as you can see, the visuals are inspired by subway maps you can find all around the world)But a minimalist game isn't a simple game. Each station has a specific shape. Imagine that a circle represents a residential district and that a triangle represents a business area. Passengers will then tend to go from a circle to triangle. And back. But as time goes, new shapes appear. And it really feels like if a city was blooming before your eyes. Again, imagine that a square is a commercial district, a star is a tourist area,  a diamond is an airport... Some of the shapes will appear in large numbers and close together. Others will be scarce but will be a favorite destination from all around the map. Again, just like in a real blooming city.Add to that the fact that a dozen of real life cites are present in the game, each with a different feel, different tools, different obstacles.To put it simply, the game is already perfect as it is. But it's still quite hard to explain and you really have to experience how it works, for it's both a very stressing and demanding gameanda most contemplative and artistic pice of work."
