,Recommended,287980,12623055,"Posted: 25 October, 2014",all,Bænlynn,"If you like the bold lines and abstract shapes of the Harry Beck-style transit map, then this is your chance to dive into one up to your armpits. It is simple to get to grips with but incredibly complex to learn, because you're dealing with an NP complete problem that keeps evolving as you play. It's laid back and relaxed but frenetic at the same time, because who knows when you'll have to redraw your entire network all of a sudden and it will test you to the limit. This game is already one of my top five all-time favourites, because until I played it I had no idea just how long I'd been waiting for it.At it's core Mini Metro is a strategy game, but not in the sense of combat, but in one of motion, logistics. Balancing the economics of time, distance and people in simple lines and abstract geometric shapes. It's easy to get into but so difficult to master, combined with the random nature of the gameplay, that gives it an incredible amount of longevity.Buy it. Buy it for a friend. Buy it for a family member. Buy it for a co-worker. Play it. Enjoy it. Love it. It's well worth the asking price."
