,Recommended,287980,19462853,"Posted: 3 December, 2015",all,nintendude794,"Mini Metro's distinct levels--all inspired by real-world metro lines--definitely have deep nuances that affect your tactics for each and reward your experimentation and practice.It's a lot like Flight Control, except more complex.I love the meditative, minimalist aesthetic, especially with Night Mode enabled. FEZ composer Disasterpeace has crafted a lush, warm, subdued soundscape full of soft sines and small clocks that grows, shrinks, or shifts dynamically in response to your actions based on conditions in the game. Though even at full volume on my laptop, it wasn't loud enough for me.At their core, simulation and management games are about optimizing a particular workflow or mastering a certain system as best as you can. Mini Metro falls into that category, even loosely--just on a smaller, less permanent scale. I admit, a larger and lasting scale of some kind would be even more interesting here, but it shares these traits of ""starting all over"" with both score-chaser Arcade games and procedurally-generated Roguelike games.Yet even with all its depth and variations, the gameplay itself is eventually too simple to be this repetitive, and too repetitive to be this simple. I guess that makes it more suited to being used as a palette cleanser between games or between life, once you've played past using it as a game. Hence the inclusion of a Daily Challenge.Overall, there is far more praiseworthy about this game than not, and too few games accomplish similar concepts this beautifully. I hope to improve at it regularly and look forward to whatever features and content future patches will bring along!"
