76561198013132245,Recommended,287980,24232045,"Posted: 10 July, 2016",all,huminado,"Minimalist graphics.Train logistics.Slow building where each scenario starts with 3 stations, then adds new stations and passengers over time.By far, what I find most satisfying about this game, is watching the train simulation, watching passengers get on and off trains.  The mechanism is the same as other train simulators and the lightweight graphics don't detract from the experience and immersion.The logistics consist of creating paths so common passenger destinations are accessible in minimal stops, while rare destinations are still handled in a timely fashion.  Also, just because a station is full and a train arrives, doesn't mean anybody will get on board, since the passengers seem to choose a train going to the nearest destination, not the earliest destination... (i.e. they'll wait a week to get on the train which has their stop next, rather than getting on this train that has their stop 2 stops down in the other direction) - at least it looked like that's what they are doing.Choose between new engine types, new routes, bridges, or carriages.  As stations become overcrowded with unserviced passengers, eventually the scenario will end, with an option to continue in endless mode.  Endless mode is fun as the game turns into mostly a free-form sandbox train station simulator.  Setting up one train to have a long chain of cars is pretty nice.I loved Sid Meier's Railroad and Mini Metro provides a lot of the same enjoyment.  Gameplay starts a little too slow, and after about 2 minutes picks up enough to become interesting.  Good tension.  Each map seems to generate stops randomly, so the same map played twice can be very different.  It would be nice to have an RNG seed interface to play the same map and station order repeatedly, but the game is still enjoyable as it is.  $10 - fair price."
