76561198054309757,Recommended,287980,17504949,"Posted: 12 August, 2015",all,ian.silver67,"Here is proof you don't need Unity5 to make a GREAT game.It looks a little like the 1970's Atari tennis - but with colour and  A LOT more little blocks moving around. It is essentially a join the dots resource management game - which sounds demeaning but it is not, this is a challenging, fun and addictive game. As the player you get a number of locomotives, carriages, lines and few other goodies with which to build an efficient underground/subway/U-Bahn in a variety of large ciities across Europe, Asia, America and Africa.Passengers mass at stations. They want to go to other stations that match their shape (triangulasr passengers want to go to traingular stations), easy enough but there are quite a few shapes. If to many passengers crowd a station the whole transport system collapses - game over. To move these people you put locomotives on the line, busy lines may mean you have to place extra locos (up tp 4 per line) going in both directions. You only have a limited number of lines and locos which have limited space so.....well you know how these things work. Intersecting train lines, tunnels under rivers and the appearance of specialised stations (hospitals for example) add to the challenge. It's all about getting people out of the system quickly so you can load the next one onto a train and get rid of him to. The problem is the more efficient your train system, the more peole want to use it, so.....well you know how these things work.More stations appear on the map over time, meaning at times a total redesign of track routes etc may be needed.The game is not finished (for example as of writing this, audio is not quite ready), but it is stable and VERY playable - but as I said one of those addicitive 'I'll play just a bit longer"" games that ends up filling your evening."
