,Recommended,287980,21057410,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,Blind Captain,"Simple: Draw metro tracks and choose how many trains go to each. No budgets, no construction time, etc.Calming: In normal mode, you lose once the metro stations start getting backed up. This prevents the game from getting hectic which makes it a nice game for destressing. It also has a minimalist interface with a calm sound scheme.Complex: While you could play it as a casual game, it's not merely a ""casual"" game. When I first started, I played it like a casual game. ""New station pops up? I'll connect the nearest metro line to it. It'd look a lot prettier if the line was more symmetrical."" You can do that, but you score in the bottom 25%. Then I realized, there is actually a ton of strategic depth to this game despite its casual appearance. Each time I play I realize new strategic factors in things that seemed like they didn't matter before. Now I'm in the top 10%. So, I think it's fair to saying it's more than a casual game. You can play it ""casually"" but you can also play it ""seriously"", analyzing every tiny detail."
