,Recommended,287980,11700466,"Posted: 14 August, 2014",all,CorporalRutland,"There's something inherently calming about joining the dots and creating order - and Mini Metro capitalises on this beautifully. Gorgeous, minimal and uncluttered design, lovely bright colours and simple shapes are the order of the day. Shaped stations pop up on the white landscape, requiring you to join them together with lines. As you do, passengers appear at them, demanding to get to other stations.The system that deals with moving passengers about, especially when to and when not to pick them up and which interchanges to drop them at seems, even in this 'early access' build, to be flawless. Short of the missing sound and music (which I can't wait for) and the so-called Scenic and Rush Hour modes (which seem to be Zen and Extreme in the version I have here) this is already a fantastic little game. Bonus points for having a night mode as well.For fear of cluttering up the minimalism I'd like to be able to name stops  for my own reference or just for fun, but otherwise, I can't wait for the last finishing touches."
