76561198027106612,Recommended,287980,14201650,"Posted: 27 January, 2015",all,Star Adept,"I just got back from work and, having barely kicked off my shoes, I went to play another round of Mini Metro. Then I noticed I have clocked over 100 hours in the two weeks that I have had this game. It is sucking my soul the way a game hasn't done since I was too young to have anything better to do than play games anyways. Now, admittedly, a portion of those hours are from me passing out with the game open, contemplating the overall efficiency of my entire subway system having been thrown a curve-ball station or two. But the difference between 100 hours total and 80 hours conscious is really not that significant, relative to overwhelming number of 0.6hrs-played games in my library. I don't normally write reviews, but I know there are casual gamers out there with similar disappointments, so this review is for you.tl:dr : Casual, strategic gamers that like to watch their decisions unfold in as perfect a manner as they can conclude, get this game! Even (especially) in Early Access!Review:I forgot this game was Early Access until I came to this page to write the review, and that's a good thing! Most of us have been victimized by vaporware, and I understand your hesitation to trust it (or really anything on steam anymore), such that our reviews are the only information worth sifting through anymore.Mini Metro is a minimalist game both visually and in its core mechanics. That being said, it does both of these things so well and uniquely, even and its current state, that it seems more polished than a large portion of the released titles that just keep pumping out. And, although I yearn for more maps (when are we ever truly satisfied), the game feels complete enough that if it went full release today, I would clock another 100 hourse easily. The only thing it's missing is sound, but that's on the list to be added and ultimately the silence doesn't really detract from the game, playing my own moodscapes in the background. I'm sure there's more content that they plan to add, but I haven't been following the devs enough to tell you what those are. And honestly, bilissfully ignorant of their promises, I can tell that any new content is just going to be a wonderful surprise as the game progresses out of Early Access, such as the newly added Rush Hour Mode (more on that later). Also what I can't tell you is how fast the game is being updated. I got this game only recently, and in that time they updated with the addition of a whole new mode, but I may have just lucked out on my timing - look to other reviews or follow the devs for this info.At its heart, Mini Metro is a game where you create a subway (or metro depending on your colloquialism) system that is as efficient as possible at delivering passengers between stations.I had gotten 1/4 the way into my original review, which was on the way to being pretty fleshed out I thought, but then I learned there is a charlimit when writing reviews. So, it's sorta lost it's cohesion but I hope I got most of my love for this game out.Stations are also abstract and minmalistic, being represented by bordered geometric shapes. All maps start you with a Circle, Square, and Triangle station, and represent the most common stations you'll see. Having no depth of explanation, it's difficult to call those stations by anything other than their shapes, only learning to conceptualize the different types as things like transfers and major stations once you learn how the stations need to be connected to be efficient later in the game. That being said, you often have to use stations as a matter of efficiency that betrays your concepts of them. This is one of the things I find special about Mini Metro. You can know the rules in and out, but your understanding of their roles changes with every new station that pops up, creating a logic of efficiency that is more conscious and fulfilling than simply figuring out the math.There is no right or wrong decision (except for Rush Hour mode) as everything you've done on the map so far can be freely and meticulously readjusted instantaneously. The few resources the game limits you with like the number of trains and bridges, when not in use, are returned to your pool of resources with zero loss; you can only get more, and will need more. Even lategame when you're struggling to keep 20-30 stations efficient as a whole, a few clicks and you can wipe the board of your entire subway for a fresh start, but without a restart back to silly ol' 3 stations. Casual, no need to dredge through a game you just played a second time to get to a point where you can use what you learned the first time, you can just continually build on your knowledge.It's actually those lategame board clears that, personally, are the most fun for me. As you progress on a map, you'll get extra trains. I only ever use one train on a line. This is extremely limiting, but I enjoy the challenge of the game that way, because without a second train to pick up the slack, lines have to be more efficient at interacting with eachother, dropping off passengers in perfect spots, running cross-track or parallel to alleviate congestion, balancing short but heavily loaded lines with long but easily resolved ones. And a board clear of infrastructure allows me to consider an efficient system as a whole instead of one in relation to what I had built already. This is normally where I pass out staring at my screen.Game Modes, since I'm not sure I've seen a review for since Rush Hour came out:The game has three modes currently, Commuter (skirmish), Scenic (peaceful), and  new Rush Hour (permabuild).The difference between Commuter mode and Scenic mode is mosty just that if you aren't being efficient enough on a Commuter map, your passengers pile up and get mad that they're stting in a station too long, you'll fail.Rush Hour is the bane of my existence. Most of what I have described is in the two modes where you can readjust your lines and resources. In Rush Hour mode, once you connect two stations, you can't unconnect them. You can extend their lines to new stations, but then you're stuck with that order of stations. Trains move down the line from one station to another, and then turn around and do the opposite order (unless you loop them). Because of this, in any game mode, adding a new station to the line affects its overall efficiency by first simply making the people at one end of the line wait longer for the train to get back, secondly because if passengers aren't getting dropped off efficiently, your train gets full and he passes by stations of people already waiting. Even extra trains, when placed, can't be picked back up. The only saving grace to this mode is that while in the other modes, stations just simply appear and you have to deal with them accordingly. In Rush Hour mode, you get to see where and what type the next station will be. I have not spent more than a few minutes in this mode as it requires a completely different mindset than the way I play the other two modes.For $7 at regularly priced Early Access, probably the most appropriately priced item I've bought on Steam.10/10 Would connect the dots for 100 more hours with even the smallest of a content boost."
