76561198045141446,Recommended,287980,18212697,"Posted: 26 September, 2015",all,recurvedshedua,"Stumbled upon this game when thumbing through the minimalistic genre. As it happens I have become quite a fan of it. Let me give a quick rundown of what happens here:* you select a map to play on* stations appear on the map* passengers appear at the stations with various destinations in mind* these stations all require the player to connect via transport lines* as time runs on, things get more hectic, more stations appear with more passengers..etcStations are denoted by shapes. Passengers appear next to the stations as a shape which tells where they want to go. For example a square station with a triangle passenger shows up you need to shuttle them to the nearest triangle station. As time goes on you will have many triangle stations on your map. The passenger does not care which triangle station you let them off on. This means the most efficient lines have all different shapes on them. Connecting a bunch of triangles together in one line is not really a good idea. Passengers that are waiting at a triangle station will never be triangle, so having the next three stations in your line be triangle is not efficient. They will ride the train until they reach their correct station, or wait at that station until the connection can be made by getting off on a station with multiple line connections that eventually lead to their destination. (basically like a hub station) This is where it gets tricky. The shapes on the map can change over time. Special shapes also appear that are rare. This means that you will undoubtedly have only one line that reaches a special shape. This will cause a buildup at the hub ""interchange"" station which for me usually ends up to be the square shape. There are many ways to play the game. Hopefully that short explanation will help new players get into the game.There are resources, in that you have a limited number of train lines, trains, passenger cars, and tunnels to traverse different map layouts that have bodies of water. You can also control the time by pausing it (which is very helpful later on in the game) or by speeding it up. It appears to me that both the stations and passengers at the station are generated randomly on the map. I am not that good at this game but maps generally last about 5-15 minutes before game over. It can get to be hectic toward the end of a round, where pausing and micromanagement comes in if you want to move 2000+ passengers before game over. This can be obtained by reworking lines, moving passenger cars and trains around, etc. You can even pick up a train and toss it back down in another direction if one half of your line is getting crowded.For a quick technical run down, this game appears to use the Unity engine, and currently uses less than 300MB of disk space. The game runs fine on Windows 10. The interface is clean and modern with large readable text. (thanks for that) The game users colors in an important way to denote lines/trains and includes a color blindness mode. The game is quite minimalistic from a graphical standpoint, using solid colors and thankfully has a night mode. Night mode dims the color palette which is amazing as I usually play this game at the evening hours in low light conditions. All good stuff here.I am no expert but here are some early tips on playing the game:* you can ""loop"" in new stations by dragging a nearby line to connect it* you can redraw a line by moving around either end of the line where there is a T marker* you can delete a line by selecting the color swatch at the bottom of the screen* you cannot cross lines when out in the open away from a station* trains and carriages can be moved from one line to another (you can even remove all trains from a line)* same as above and you can place the train back down going in the opposite direction* try to make sure lines do not have the same shaped station connected in a row* don't forget special station shapes and make sure multiple lines can see them* keep on the lookout for shapes in your line to change, this happens and can go unnoticed* spacebar key will pause and resume the gameC = circleS = squareT = triangle(the most common shapes are C and T, S being less common and specials not included into below basic examples)Example of good lines:  CST, CTCSTCT, TCTSCTCExample of bad lines: CCC, CSCCCCT, TSTCTTTTThe good idea above is to try and center the SQUARE station so it isn't all the way at the end of a line. It is a semi-rare station so on a long line it is helpful to have in the middle ground. Also note the rotation between common shapes, this allows trains to dump the passengers right off at the next station. The bad line has connections of same shaped stations together, with the semi-rare SQUARE at the far end of a line. It gets much more complicated as the game runs on but hopefully this helps explain the idea.Glad I purchased this game, and thanks to the developer for making it![edited in full review content]"
