76561197967900181,Recommended,287980,12684628,"Posted: 29 October, 2014",all,Brandon,"I'm not really sure what it is about this little indie game, but seriously, if the subject matter interests you at all, then I recommend you pick it up.It is, by far, one of the most compulsively playable titles I have set my hands on in quite some time. Even though it resides in the early access areas of Steam, it can comfortably sit beside others that are deemed to be finished. The only thing missing from this game is sound. That being said, the sound is something I couldn't care less about. It is the least of my concern as I continue to further the efficiency and optimal layout of my subway lines.The game itself is played through various stages, in this case, cities of the world. Each stage provides you with a basic layout map and routes or ""lines"" to place between stations. The stations are represented as shapes on the map that you must connect using your lines. As you do so additional symbols are shown on the map to represent the passengers.   Your locomotives move around the map autonomously along your set routes picking up and dropping off passengers as they go. This would present itself as an easy puzzle to solve, however, as the days and weeks go by in game, that couldn't be farther from the truth. It becomes a complex balancing act to try to get passengers to and fro as quickly as possible without allowing them to build up at an individual stations. This, as far as I can tell, is the only end game state. If a station has too many passengers, the countdown begins until finally the game notifies you of your defeat.The game is so simple and elegant, yet complex and harsh, all at the same time. I haven't played anything like it before. It sits by itself in a world of indie games that are increasinging in quality all the time, yet somehow all have a familiar feeling. This eschews that familiarity for something altogether different. Something playable, satisfying, and ultimately, something worth spending your hard earned money on to enjoy fully.If you aren't sure that you would in fact enjoy it, I recommend you go online and type in Mini Metro in your search engine of choice. There you will find a link to the developers ""alpha"" version of the game. It is very bare bones compared to what we have here, but it will no doubt allow you to get a taste of things for yourself. I don't think you'll be disappointed.Highly recommended!  10/10"
