76561198045966388,Recommended,287980,27658031,"Posted: 26 November, 2016",all,Acherrum,"I was looking for a relaxing casual game, when I found this...A few days before the release of a game I've been excited for, I always get this restless feeling and I have no apetite for any of the games in my library. So I always start to wonder through the Steam store aimlessly, seeing if anything tickles my fancy.I then stumbled upon Mini Metro. I had seen it before, but never thought much of it. This time, I decided to pick it up (at 40% discount) after watching some of the reviews on youtube again. Boy, does this game tickle that ""too excited about an upcoming release that I don't want to play any of my current games""-spot perfectly!I started it up, played through the tutorial and 2 hours later I decided I really had to turn it off and prepare for bed (it was 2AM at this time). Today, I decided to show the girlfriend this wonderful new puzzle game and an hour later she's apparently left the house and I'm still clicking and dragging away to make sure that every passenger gets to it's destination before they get too angry.The gameplay is simple: connect the shapes (stations) so that the passengers get to their destination as fast as possible.The longer passengers have to wait, the angrier they get. Combine this with the RNG nature of the shapes, the upgrades/resources you get and the ever growing city population that wants to travel by metro, and you've got a chaotic and challenging puzzle game that's oddly relaxing at the same time.The game has daily challenges (with leaderboards) for repeated gameplay, a bunch of different maps with different gameplay elements to make sure you don't get bored too easily.Whether or not it's worth 10 bucks, totally depends on how much you like puzzle games.A great puzzle game!"
