76561198035343655,Recommended,287980,28925289,Posted: 1 January,all,hjdeputy4,Clever gameplay and presentation.  Purchased the game on sale and it has been worth every penny.
76561197985434824,Recommended,287980,25809305,"Posted: 1 October, 2016",all,bewbays,"I'm writing this review to allow the reader to determine whether or not the game is worth the designated price and if they would like to invest time into this game. There is a tl;dr after the Plus and Minus section.░▒▓█Design█▓▒░The design of the game is minimalistic and does excellent work of duplicating the style and visual communication of modern metro systems. Navigating through the menus feels very clean and the animations fit perfectly into the concept of the game. One major plus is the inclusion of ""Night Mode"" which changes the games background to black. The option is there if your eyes get strained, which is nice. The developers also included a ""Colorblind Mode"" (basically a deuteranopia simulator) which I thought was an interesting addition to a game. Not entirely sure if this was meant to compensate for deuteranopia, as I am not afflicted with that particular colour blindness. The font and typeface in the game certainly gives the impression of ""Metro System"" and were well chosen and utilized. In the level selection screen there is definitely an arcade-like design and mechanic  in the way it is presented to the player. The concept, design, animation and mechanics of this game are very strong, I really enjoy it. 8/10░▒▓█Gameplay█▓▒░So: there are three primary shapes. In the order of most to least frequent: Circles, Triangles and Squares. At the beginning, the game will instruct you to connect a Circle to a Square. Your job as the player is to continue connecting one shape to another to create a network in which passengers can travel through as fast and efficiently as possible. At each shape, smaller black shapes will begin showing up, these are the passengers. The passengers shape corresponds to where their destination is (i.e. a triangle passenger goes to a triangle shape). As the game progresses, new unique shapes and passengers are introduced. At the end of each week (Sunday) the player is left with various choices such as starting a new line, getting a new locomotive to carry passengers, getting a speed train, getting a terminal to house more passengers without overcrowding, getting a carriage to increase the quantity of passengers that the player can carry on a line and getting tunnels/bridges to travel through water.Right off the bat, when booting up the game for the first time, takes you right into the tutorial, which basically drops you in the game and relies on you trying to figure it out for yourself... It basically forces you to start the first mission (London) right within the ""tutorial"" (if you can even call it that). You will probably fail and have to restart like I did, but at that point you know the basics and mechanics of the game (how to connect lines and develop a system).The pacing of the game is good, the 3 levels it starts you off with are a good training ground for what is about to come. The difficulty increases quite fluidly with each passing level. Once you get to Hong Kong (at least for me) that's when the game becomes more difficult and at this point is when you will have to start retrying and replaying the level. It can get frustrating. Before Hong Kong you can just kind of wing it and the system will probably work. You have the option of restarting at any point, which can be advantageous at the beginning of the level. If your three starting points (square, triangle, circle) are in a not-so-desirable configuration, the player can just restart the level for a new starting configuration.One flaw, which after reading the community hub is a pretty major one, is that there is no numerical indication for how many locomotives and carriages you have on a line. Which would prove to be very useful to know and keep track of. There were times when playing where I would neglect to put a locomotive on a line and just forget about it until it was too late. 7.5/10░▒▓█Sound█▓▒░Full transparency: the sound/music in this game gets quite annoying after about 1-2 hours. It starts off ambient and somewhat subdued and relaxed, but quickly becomes obnoxious the more you play. In addition to this, the ticking sound when a station becomes overcrowded is just absolutely unnerving. A user in the review section recommended putting your own music on whilst playing this game, and I absolutely agree. There really isn't anything important, sound-wise, that would require the player to focus on sound (other than station overcrowding, which can be argued, is negligible to require sound). The sound is probably the weakest component in this game, as evident in the games options, which gives the player only two options: sound on/off. 4/10░▒▓█Plus█▓▒░♦ Excellent design.♦ Good pacing and appropriate increase of difficulty.♦ Very effective visual communication, game is straightforward and easy to figure out.♦ Game layout is well executed.♦ Can continue in Endless Mode after you have failed in Normal Mode.♦ Inclusion of Night Mode to combat eye strain.♦ Good replay value░▒▓█Minus█▓▒░♦ Sound is annoying. Grows tiring quite quickly. On/off is the only choice in the Options Menu for sound.♦ Beating Normal Mode doesn't take too long and the game is quite short lived.♦ Minimal GUI.♦ Limited game variables and editable options.░▒▓█Conclusion tl;dr█▓▒░In my honest opinion, this game is definitely worth the $10.99CAD that I paid. I got my monies worth and then some. The game has a strong and successful design philosophy with an emphasis on mass visual communication and logic/puzzle/strategy. The pacing of levels is effective and appropriate in correspondence with increase in difficulty. Sound is annoying and the game has limited variables and editable options, but all around great game. Replay value is good, depending on individual interest. Recommended.7.720/108/10 *see 2017 edit below*Total time played (at time of review): 7.8 hrsTotal time taken to complete normal mode (all levels): 3hrs 46mins░▒▓█EDIT 05/01/2017█▓▒░Since the date this review was made public (October 2016) Dinosaur Polo Club has patched bugs in the build which I first started playing, they have now allowed for lines to cross each other and have added 3 new non-DLC levels: San Francisco, Seoul and Shanghai. This just goes to show that the developers are committed to improving the game and remain in close correspondence with the community."
