,Recommended,287980,30111499,Posted: 22 February,all,The Sound of Dunder,"A charming little puzzle game that has you running a city inhabited by little shape people, and it's your job as the person running the metro system to get them to where they wanna be. You're given a number of lines and trains that your metro system can have and you need to create a system that can get everyone where they need to be as well as acommodate for additional stops that you have to tend to and make sure that it stays well-run. I love this game! It's really chill and pleasing to look at, opting for nothing but solid colors and simple shapes. I recommend it to anyone who is looking for a game they can pop a round of during a break or something. It's also on mobile devices as well."
76561198040032136,Recommended,287980,29875587,Posted: 12 February,all,Nat3ski,"A game so nice I bought it twice!This is a brilliant game which has a charming, minimalist art style reminiscent of the London Underground Tube map.The controls are intuitive, both on PC and on the Android version, and the game is addictive and fun!You are tasked with connecting an ever growing number of stations in some of the worlds most iconic cities, reprsented by simple shapes which denote the type of station. At these stations passengers will gather, their destination denoted by the shape of the passenger resembling that of station they wish to reach.You will need to get these passengers to their destination before the station overcrowds. A progressively more difficult task as the number of stations and passengers increases.To achieve this, you will need to carefully manage a limited number of trains, carriages, lines and bridges. These are granted to you on a weekly basis, often presented as an 'either/ or' choice.This is where the challenge lies, becasue if any station overcrowds, it's game over.There are a number of different levels to play, daily challenges and the developers are working on an endless mode,  last I heard. Available on PC, Android & IOS and is equally good across all."
